stressed that Pence didn't
always directly
defend Trump's record, including
his refusal

09:44.584 --> 09:45.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to release tax records.

09:45.885 --> 09:47.720 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

09:47.754 --> 09:50.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM KAINE: Every president since
Richard Nixon
has done it, and Donald Trump
has said: I'm

09:50.323 --> 09:51.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
doing business with Russia.

09:51.991 --> 09:54.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only way the American public
will see
whether he has a conflict of
interest...

09:54.427 --> 09:55.395 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

09:55.428 --> 09:56.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE PENCE: No, he hasn't said
that.

09:56.429 --> 09:57.397 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

09:57.430 --> 09:58.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TIM KAINE: He has, actually.

09:58.398 --> 09:59.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELAINE QUIJANO: Senator, your
time is up.

09:59.966 --> 10:00.934 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Governor?

10:00.967 --> 10:01.935 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

10:01.968 --> 10:03.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MIKE PENCE: Well, thanks.

10:03.837 --> 10:06.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm just trying to keep up with
the insult-driven
campaign on the other side of
the table.

10:06.439 --> 10:07.807 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

10:07.841 --> 10:08.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM KAINE: You know, I'm just
saying facts
about your running mate.

10:08.942 --> 10:09.909 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

10:09.943 --> 10:10.910 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MIKE PENCE: Yes.

10:10.944 --> 10:11.911 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

10:11.945 --> 10:13.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TIM KAINE: And I know you can't
defend.

10:13.780 --> 10:14.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: The Clinton
campaign quickly
put out a video ad contrasting
Pence's words

10:14.848 --> 10:15.815 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Trump's.

10:15.849 --> 10:17.183 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

10:17.217 --> 10:18.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM KAINE: Donald Trump said,
keep them out
if they're Muslim.

10:18.751 --> 10:19.719 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mike Pence...

10:19.752 --> 10:20.720 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

10:20.753 --> 10:21.855 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MIKE PENCE: Absolutely...

10:21.888 --> 10:23.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Total and complete
shutdown
of Muslims.

10:23.623 --> 10:27.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But Kaine
raised questions
with his statement on the
Iranian nuclear

10:27.727 --> 10:32.565 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
agreement negotiated by
Secretary of State
John Kerry, but teed up by
sanctions that

10:32.599 --> 10:33.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Clinton brokered.

10:33.600 --> 10:35.335 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

10:35.368 --> 10:39.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM KAINE: She worked a tough
negotiation
with nations around the world to
eliminate

10:39.806 --> 10:42.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Iranian nuclear weapons
program without
firing a shot.

10:42.709 --> 10:43.910 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

10:43.943 --> 10:44.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE PENCE: Eliminate the
Iranian nuclear
weapons program?

10:44.711 --> 10:45.678 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

10:45.712 --> 10:47.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TIM KAINE: Absolutely, without
firing a shot.

10:47.514 --> 10:50.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: In fact, Iran
did agree never
to acquire nuclear weapons, but
opponents

10:50.683 --> 10:55.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the deal point out Tehran
will keep some
nuclear ability and could
renege.

10:55.688 --> 11:02.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, with 34 days left, the
campaigns are fighting
over facts and fighting for
every vote.

11:02.262 --> 11:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lisa
Desjardins.

11:07.534 --> 11:18.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: From the race for
the White
House, we turn to the start of a
new term

11:18.177 --> 11:21.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the Supreme Court, and to
Jeffrey Brown.

11:21.114 --> 11:25.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And a most
unusual term it
is, with an empty seat since the
death of

11:25.351 --> 11:27.353 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Antonin Scalia last February.

11:27.387 --> 11:31.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's been at least 25 years
since the court
began a term with just eight
members.

11:31.925 --> 11:37.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We look at that and at a case
argued today
about racial bias and the death
penalty.

11:37.096 --> 11:41.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we welcome back our favorite
court watcher,
Marcia Coyle of "The National
Law Journal."

11:41.568 --> 11:42.769 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

11:42.802 --> 11:43.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National Law
Journal":
Thanks, Jeff.

11:43.570 --> 11:44.537 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Welcome back.

11:44.571 --> 11:45.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Time to get to work.

11:45.572 --> 11:46.539 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

11:46.573 --> 11:47.540 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Absolutely.

11:47.574 --> 11:49.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

11:49.409 --> 11:51.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a term in which the court
begins shorthanded,
what impact are we seeing, might
we see?

11:51.377 --> 11:53.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What jumps out at you?

11:53.212 --> 11:56.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, I think,
right now, what
we see has to do with the kinds
of cases that

11:56.849 --> 12:00.253 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the court has already accepted
for decision.

12:00.286 --> 12:06.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There are no potential
blockbuster issues
on the docket of the kind that
seemed to mark

12:06.726 --> 12:10.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just about every term of the
Roberts court
since it began in 2005.

12:10.229 --> 12:11.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There have always
been a couple
at least.

12:12.031 --> 12:13.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's right.

12:13.900 --> 12:19.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, instead, the cases that
we're seeing,
there is a healthy dose of
patent, arbitration,

12:19.672 --> 12:25.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bankruptcy, and there are more
narrow technical
statutory interpretation cases.

12:25.211 --> 12:32.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I would say, Jeff, there
have been other
terms that began rather low-key,
low-profile,

12:32.218 --> 12:35.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it only takes one to raise
the profile.

12:35.388 --> 12:39.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The justices will continue to
add cases through
the middle of January.

12:39.759 --> 12:44.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But without knowing what's in
every justices'
mind, I have a feeling this
court right now

12:44.130 --> 12:47.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is happy to have a low profile
during this
election campaign.

12:47.634 --> 12:50.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And we should
just say -- I
mean, we talk about this often,
but the court

12:50.536 --> 12:52.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
gets to decide what cases it
will take.

12:52.472 --> 12:54.173 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: It does.

12:54.207 --> 12:57.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, you're
suggesting that
the thinking might be, let
things simmer a

12:57.744 --> 13:03.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
little bit, or maybe some cases
that are too
hot for an eight-member panel
might be worth

13:03.182 --> 13:04.984 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not taking.

13:05.018 --> 13:07.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: I think so,
because, certainly,
in the calculus of accepting a
case, they

13:07.387 --> 13:12.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to think, will we be able
to get five
votes, a majority, to decide it?

13:12.125 --> 13:16.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if that's questionable, they
may veer
away from that particular case.

13:17.030 --> 13:22.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, now,
no blockbusters,
but a lot of cases I see with a
theme around

13:23.002 --> 13:24.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
race or racial bias.

13:24.270 --> 13:25.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes.

13:25.571 --> 13:27.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One was argued
today, a death
penalty case.

13:27.740 --> 13:29.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's right.

13:29.509 --> 13:34.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, race plays a central
role or even
a smaller role in three types of
cases this

13:34.747 --> 13:40.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
term, criminal justice cases,
the drawing
of electoral maps, and even
mortgage lending.

13:40.086 --> 13:46.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, today, the court focused on
criminal
justice and Duane Buck's case.

13:46.059 --> 13:48.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Buck is a Texas death row
inmate.

13:48.361 --> 13:56.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His trial back in the mid-1990s,
his own defense
counsel at that trial introduced
an expert

13:56.669 --> 14:03.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
witness who testified to a
stereotype, a terrible
stereotype that's been debunked
for years

14:03.443 --> 14:05.078 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

14:05.111 --> 14:10.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He testified that, because Buck
was black,
he was more likely to be
dangerous in the

14:10.717 --> 14:12.485 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
future.

14:12.518 --> 14:17.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Future dangerousness is a
special issue that
Texas jurors have to agree
unanimously to

14:17.590 --> 14:21.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in order to impose the death
sentence, and
they did so here.

14:21.461 --> 14:24.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, he's not --
in this case,
just to be clear, he's not
challenging the

14:24.597 --> 14:25.565 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
conviction.

14:25.598 --> 14:27.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: No.

14:27.400 --> 14:29.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He's challenging
the sentencing,
which -- with the claim that it
was based

14:29.902 --> 14:30.870 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a racial bias.

14:30.903 --> 14:32.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's exactly
right.

14:32.038 --> 14:33.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what happened
in the court
today?

14:33.406 --> 14:34.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What was the argument?

14:34.741 --> 14:37.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, the court
seemed sympathetic
to Mr. Buck.

14:37.777 --> 14:42.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even Justice Alito said that
what happened
in that trial was indefensible.

14:42.548 --> 14:46.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the problem for the court is
really, how
are they going to deal with
this?

14:46.419 --> 14:50.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a very procedurally
complicated case.

14:50.456 --> 14:55.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the chief justice asked
Buck's attorney,
what do you want us to do here?

14:55.394 --> 15:01.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you want to us say, on one
hand, this was
a clear violation of the
Constitution, Mr.

15:01.701 --> 15:04.737 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Buck, he gets a new sentencing
hearing?

15:04.771 --> 15:10.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Or do we address the issue that
the attorney
actually raised, and that is,
did the lower

15:10.209 --> 15:17.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
federal appellate court use the
right standard
in denying Buck what we call a
certificate

15:17.550 --> 15:22.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of appealability, which would
have enabled
him to go back to a federal
district court,

15:22.522 --> 15:27.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reopen his habeas petition to
argue that he
deserves a new sentencing
hearing?

15:27.693 --> 15:31.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, in this case,
the possible
outcomes are unclear.

15:31.364 --> 15:32.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's right.

15:32.465 --> 15:33.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But the sentiment
seemed to
be...

15:33.432 --> 15:35.334 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: I think so.

15:35.368 --> 15:39.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It seemed pretty clear across
the bench that
they definitely had a problem
with what happened

15:39.138 --> 15:40.873 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at his trial.

15:40.907 --> 15:42.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just in our last
minute, let
me come back to the larger
picture, because

15:42.942 --> 15:43.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you said no blockbusters.

15:43.943 --> 15:45.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes.

15:45.378 --> 15:46.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But there are a
few out there
that they might take.

15:46.145 --> 15:47.113 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

15:47.146 --> 15:48.915 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Oh, absolutely.

15:48.948 --> 15:51.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just because they may be small
or narrow or
low-profile doesn't mean they're
unimportant

15:51.818 --> 15:53.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or uninteresting.

15:53.386 --> 15:57.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The court has, for example, an
interesting
religion case.

15:57.857 --> 16:06.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trinity Lutheran Church in
Missouri is challenging
Missouri's denial of state
grants to it to

16:06.265 --> 16:12.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resurface a playground, claiming
that it discriminates
against religious institutions,
that violates

16:12.205 --> 16:13.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the First Amendment.

16:13.573 --> 16:18.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Oregon rock group the Slants
is involved
in a trademark case.

16:18.811 --> 16:26.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their mark was turned down by a
federal agency
because it disparaged Asian
Americans.

16:26.419 --> 16:30.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A federal appellate court struck
that law
down as violating the
Constitution.

16:30.823 --> 16:34.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Obama administration is
asking the Supreme
Court to take a look at it.

16:34.093 --> 16:37.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And some very
high-profile
-- there's a transgender case
that could...

16:37.897 --> 16:39.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: This is in the
wings, right.

16:39.065 --> 16:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the wings.

16:40.967 --> 16:44.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: There's a petition
from a Virginia
county school board that's
challenging a lower

16:44.737 --> 16:50.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
court's order that a transgender
boy should
be able to use the boys'
bathroom.

16:50.376 --> 16:54.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's also an interesting
case, sort
of continued fallout from
same-sex marriage,

16:55.014 --> 17:01.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where a Colorado baker said his
religious
beliefs prevented him from
baking a wedding

17:01.487 --> 17:04.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cake for a same-sex couple.

17:04.090 --> 17:08.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Colorado's Civil Rights
Commission found that
the baker violated the public
accommodations

17:08.594 --> 17:09.729 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
law.

17:09.762 --> 17:12.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The baker has brought a petition
to the Supreme
Court.

17:12.164 --> 17:15.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They could definitely raise the
temperature
of the court if it takes it.

17:15.801 --> 17:17.069 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Absolutely.

17:17.103 --> 17:18.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
OK, Marcia Coyle, "The National
Law Journal,"
welcome back.

17:18.504 --> 17:19.472 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Thank you.

17:19.505 --> 17:21.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My pleasure, Jeff.

17:21.307 --> 17:27.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And online,
there's more on
the case of Duane Edward Buck on
our Web site,

17:27.113 --> 17:30.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PBS.org/NewsHour.

17:30.316 --> 17:41.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the second
of our three
reports this week on the fight
for Iraq.

17:41.494 --> 17:47.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Militia groups, made up mostly
of Shia fighters,
and many backed by Iran, have
become instrumental

17:47.333 --> 17:50.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the battle to drive ISIS from
Iraq.

17:50.336 --> 17:54.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But their presence on the
battlefield makes
them a controversial force, one
with which

17:54.507 --> 17:57.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the United States has deadly
familiarity.

