18:03.115 --> 18:06.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jane Ferguson and producer Jon
Gerberg report.

18:06.852 --> 18:14.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: These young men
are holding
the line on a remote hilltop
north of Tikrit.

18:14.927 --> 18:20.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They fire at any movement across
the oil fields
on the horizon, where ISIS
snipers are dug

18:20.232 --> 18:23.769 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

18:23.803 --> 18:25.004 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Conditions are rudimentary.

18:25.037 --> 18:27.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Each fighter has little with him
beyond his
gun.

18:27.540 --> 18:31.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AHMED, Hashd al-Shaabi (through
translator):
The end of ISIS is on my mind.

18:31.410 --> 18:34.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Ahmed is not part
of the Iraqi
army.

18:34.814 --> 18:40.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is a member of Iraq's Hashd
al-Shaabi,
also known as Popular
Mobilization Unit.

18:40.953 --> 18:46.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are predominantly Shia
militias, and
radical Sunni group ISIS, or
Da'esh, as they're

18:46.459 --> 18:49.161 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
called here, is their sworn
enemy.

18:49.195 --> 18:53.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AHMED (through translator): My
ambition is
the end of Da'esh in Iraq.

18:53.766 --> 18:58.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I came in response to the fatwa,
the doctrine
to defend my country, my sacred
places.

18:58.804 --> 19:02.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My wish in life is the end of
Da'esh in Iraq.

19:02.141 --> 19:08.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Like thousands of
other Shia
Iraqis, Ahmed heard the call of
Iraq's senior

19:08.147 --> 19:16.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Shia leader, Ayatollah Ali
Sistani, who in
June 2014 issued a religious
command, or fatwa,

19:16.122 --> 19:19.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to take up arms and drive ISIS
from Iraq.

19:19.725 --> 19:24.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraq's security forces had
collapsed when
ISIS rushed in from Syria and
seized a third

19:24.230 --> 19:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the country, killing Shias,
who they believe
to be heretics.

19:27.967 --> 19:33.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while the military was in
chaos, tens
of thousands of young Iraqi men
flocked to

19:33.773 --> 19:35.541 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the militias instead.

19:35.574 --> 19:39.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AHMED (through translator): The
fatwa opened
the door for us, so we
volunteered with the

19:39.945 --> 19:41.347 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hashd militia.

19:41.380 --> 19:43.115 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Ours is a belief and a will.

19:43.149 --> 19:46.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We came because of our belief,
not for a salary
or anything else.

19:46.685 --> 19:50.022 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We came because of our belief
and our principles.

19:50.056 --> 19:56.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: These troops have
come from
Southern Iraq, and they're
holding the front

19:56.729 --> 19:58.497 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
line in this whole area.

19:58.531 --> 20:03.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Iraqi army are nowhere to be
seen, and
they are camped down here, with
ISIS positions

20:03.936 --> 20:05.938 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
just over the front line.

20:05.971 --> 20:10.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many of these fighters, who have
lived for
months on the front lines now,
were civilians

20:10.543 --> 20:13.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with no military experience
until they faced
ISIS.

20:13.979 --> 20:19.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUMAA AL-AYAME, Hashd al-Shaabi
(through translator):
Even the army didn't take in
volunteers in

20:19.218 --> 20:20.286 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
such numbers.

20:20.319 --> 20:22.088 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have huge numbers.

20:22.121 --> 20:24.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We came like this, no training
centers, nothing.

20:24.590 --> 20:27.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Their presence
has been essential
to the battle.

20:28.027 --> 20:32.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS has been pushed back from
many areas,
and the Hashd militias have
played a major

20:32.998 --> 20:35.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
role in battles against the
group.

20:35.701 --> 20:44.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the actions of heavily armed
Shia fighters
in Sunni areas of Iraq have been
deeply divisive.

20:45.010 --> 20:49.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're also accused of war
crimes, such as
beheadings, killings, and
torture of Sunni

20:49.682 --> 20:52.384 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
residents in areas they have
fought in.

20:52.418 --> 20:56.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Human Rights Watch has called on
the Iraqi
government to rein them in,
saying that, in

20:56.856 --> 21:01.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
vengeance for ISIS atrocities,
they have attacked
Sunni communities.

21:01.827 --> 21:06.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Belkis Wille is senior Iraq
researcher for
Human Rights Watch based in
Kiev.

21:06.799 --> 21:08.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We spoke with her via Skype.

21:08.534 --> 21:12.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BELKIS WILLE, Human Rights
Watch: These are
segments of the population that
are being

21:12.204 --> 21:19.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
singled out for allegiance with
ISIS, whether
or not these individual members
of the community

21:19.712 --> 21:22.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are actually affiliated with
ISIS.

21:22.515 --> 21:29.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Popular Mobilization
Forces has chosen
to really single out this
community and to

21:29.188 --> 21:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
carry out these revenge attacks
on them outside
of the military structure.

21:36.428 --> 21:40.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have this ability to carry
out these
abuses, to carry out these
revenge attacks

21:41.000 --> 21:42.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with complete impunity.

21:42.801 --> 21:47.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: When Fallujah
city was retaken
from ISIS in June, the Hashd
al-Shaabi were

21:47.106 --> 21:51.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accused of detaining over 1,000
men who fled
the city.

21:51.177 --> 21:55.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some 600 are still reportedly
missing.

21:55.247 --> 21:58.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a problem for the
U.S.-led coalition.

21:58.117 --> 22:04.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Hashd al-Shaabi militias are
fighting
alongside U.S.-backed Iraqi army
forces and

22:04.123 --> 22:05.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
benefiting from American
airstrikes.

22:05.925 --> 22:07.693 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

22:07.726 --> 22:10.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN DORRIAN, Coalition
Spokesperson: Prime
Minister Abadi has said that
those alleged

22:10.596 --> 22:16.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
abuses definitely need to be
investigated,
and those responsible, if they
did occur,

22:16.235 --> 22:17.970 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
need to be held to account.

22:18.003 --> 22:24.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we're going to work with the
Iraqis on
making sure that we set
conditions to reduce

22:24.243 --> 22:27.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
as much as we can the
possibility for human
rights abuses.

22:27.980 --> 22:30.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it's a very complicated
battlefield.

22:30.349 --> 22:36.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Shia militias
like these are
funded and supported by Iran and
are a powerful

22:36.722 --> 22:41.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tool of influence for the
Iranian regime on
their neighbor Iraq.

22:41.093 --> 22:44.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is plenty of bad blood
between them
and the U.S. military.

22:44.964 --> 22:50.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of these groups were
responsible for
killing American soldiers during
the war here,

22:50.302 --> 22:55.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seen by many as Iran's way of
bleeding the
U.S. effort, says Michael
Eisenstadt.

22:55.741 --> 23:00.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He served as both a civilian and
an army officer
in Iraq during the occupation.

23:00.512 --> 23:02.348 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is now at the Washington
Institute.

23:02.381 --> 23:04.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL EISENSTADT, Washington
Institute for
Near East Policy: Many of them
were involved

23:04.450 --> 23:08.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a low-level insurgency
against the United
States and have American -- the
blood of American

23:08.921 --> 23:10.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
soldiers on their hands.

23:10.189 --> 23:12.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't want to operate in the
same battle
space as them.

23:12.891 --> 23:14.727 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It creates a lot of problems.

23:14.760 --> 23:19.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Yet, as a major
force fighting
ISIS, they are technically on
the same side

23:19.465 --> 23:21.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as the U.S. in this war.

23:21.533 --> 23:24.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
However, their commander views
America with
deep suspicion.

23:24.970 --> 23:30.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAFAR HASSAN, Hashd al-Shaabi
(through translator):
Hashd al-Shaabi doesn't trust
America.

23:30.809 --> 23:32.511 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're not here to fight ISIS.

23:32.544 --> 23:34.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are here to fight ISIS and
fight them properly.

23:35.014 --> 23:41.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: In fact, to him,
the Americans
have other intentions beyond
ISIS or even

23:41.453 --> 23:43.289 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Iraq.

23:43.322 --> 23:47.393 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAFAR HASSAN (through
translator): They want
to control Arab countries and
establish bases

23:47.426 --> 23:48.827 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
close to Iran.

23:48.861 --> 23:50.996 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have intentions against
Iran, clearly.

23:51.030 --> 23:55.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: But America's
support of Iraq's
security forces has effectively
brought the

23:55.668 --> 23:59.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. into an indirect alliance
with Iranian-backed
groups.

23:59.938 --> 24:02.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is not by choice, says
Eisenstadt.

24:02.141 --> 24:06.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL EISENSTADT: But they
also play a role
in Iraq's efforts to emerge as
the dominant

24:06.545 --> 24:11.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outside power in Iraq and to
kind of supplant
the U.S. in this role.

24:11.450 --> 24:15.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't have control over who
participates
in the fight on the ground,
although we're

24:15.154 --> 24:19.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
putting a lot of pressure on the
Iraqi military
not to rely on these groups.

24:19.925 --> 24:24.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: After this
battle, the tens
of thousands of young recruits
to the Shia

24:24.363 --> 24:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
militias will have to find a new
purpose.

24:27.966 --> 24:34.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AHMED (through translator): When
Da'esh ends
in Iraq, I'm going to work.

24:34.573 --> 24:37.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When this fatwa was first
issued, I was sitting
doing nothing.

24:37.409 --> 24:41.046 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If I finish, I will go back to
the way I was.

24:41.080 --> 24:45.818 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JANE FERGUSON: They are,
however, unlikely
to all return home.

24:45.851 --> 24:52.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the continued existence of
armed militias
beyond full government control
could destabilize

24:52.224 --> 24:55.394 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Iraq long after ISIS is gone.

24:55.427 --> 25:05.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jane
Ferguson
in Tikrit, Iraq.

25:05.371 --> 25:12.444 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

25:12.478 --> 25:18.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": how
pregnant
women in Miami are reacting to
Zika threats;

25:18.250 --> 25:23.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the important, but complex
discoveries
behind the Nobel Prizes
explained.

25:23.222 --> 25:29.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: The French government
today announced
a renewed push for a cease-fire
in Syria,

25:29.094 --> 25:31.363 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
after a previous deal failed.

25:31.397 --> 25:36.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The two architects of that
accord, Secretary
of State Kerry and Russian
Foreign Minister

25:36.402 --> 25:40.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sergei Lavrov, spoke again today
by phone.

25:40.072 --> 25:46.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meantime, the push by Syrian
forces to retake
Aleppo's rebel-held sectors
continued, as

25:46.745 --> 25:52.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a humanitarian catastrophe
mounted.

25:52.584 --> 25:58.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As rescuers on the ground in
Eastern Aleppo
sifted through the ruins by
hand, United Nations

25:58.624 --> 26:04.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
satellite images from high above
showed the
sweeping destruction.

26:04.196 --> 26:12.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Syrian military announced
today it's reducing
the land and air bombardment to
let some 275,000

26:12.538 --> 26:14.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
civilians evacuate.

26:14.840 --> 26:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Pablo Marco leads the Doctors
Without Borders
mission in Syria.

26:19.044 --> 26:21.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He spoke, via Skype, from Amman,
Jordan:

26:21.346 --> 26:25.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PABLO MARCO, Doctors Without
Borders: Unfortunately,
we have got at different moments
promises

26:25.751 --> 26:30.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the Russian government and
also from
the Syrian government about the
cease-fires,

26:30.989 --> 26:37.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
truces, a reduction of fighting,
and, honestly,
we need to see it happen before
believing

26:37.196 --> 26:39.064 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

26:39.097 --> 26:43.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Prospects for
peace were briefly
brighter last month, when
Secretary of State

26:43.068 --> 26:49.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Kerry and Russian Foreign
Minister Sergei
Lavrov brokered a cease-fire.

26:49.608 --> 26:56.849 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But Syrian and Russian
airstrikes quickly
resumed in a new and devastating
offensive

26:56.882 --> 27:02.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
against Aleppo, and an aid
convoy was bombed
near the city.

27:02.054 --> 27:07.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Monday, the State Department
severed direct
contact with Russia on the issue
of Syria.

27:07.392 --> 27:11.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KERRY, U.S. Secretary of
State: Together,
the Syrian regime and Russia
seem to have

27:11.430 --> 27:15.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
rejected diplomacy in
furtherance of trying
to pursue a military victory.

27:15.367 --> 27:20.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: At the White
House today, top
advisers grappled with what to
do next.

27:20.205 --> 27:26.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Washington Post reported
military strikes
against Syrian government forces
are an option.

27:26.445 --> 27:31.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So far, President Obama has
refused to go
that far, and The New York Times
obtained

27:31.884 --> 27:37.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a recording of Secretary Kerry
voicing frustration
last month to the Syrian
opposition.

27:37.556 --> 27:39.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN KERRY: I have argued for
use of force.

27:39.358 --> 27:41.126 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I stood up.

27:41.159 --> 27:43.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm the guy who stood up and
announced we're
going to attack Assad because of
the weapons.

27:43.262 --> 27:49.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, you know, things
evolved into a
different process.

27:49.801 --> 27:55.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Syria is also
echoing across
the presidential campaign, as in
last night's

27:55.841 --> 27:56.909 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
vice presidential debate.

27:56.942 --> 27:58.810 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

27:58.844 --> 28:00.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE PENCE (R-IN), Vice
Presidential Candidate:
The United States of America
should be prepared

28:00.245 --> 28:04.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to use military force to strike
military targets
of the Assad regime.

28:04.383 --> 28:06.218 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

28:06.251 --> 28:07.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TIM KAINE (D-VA), Vice
Presidential Candidate:
The notion is, we have to create
a humanitarian

28:07.452 --> 28:08.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
zone in Northern Syria.

28:08.654 --> 28:10.422 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's very important.

28:10.455 --> 28:16.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But the ravaged
landscape of
Aleppo begs the question: If
peace ever does

28:16.261 --> 28:20.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
come, will there be anything
left to save?

28:20.165 --> 28:24.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And to talk about what comes
next in Syria,
I'm joined now by Derek Chollet.

28:24.937 --> 28:28.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He's a former assistant
secretary of defense
in the Obama administration.

28:28.473 --> 28:30.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's now at the German Marshall
Fund.

28:31.009 --> 28:37.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Randa Slim, she's director of
the Track II
Dialogues initiative at the
Middle East Institute.

28:37.849 --> 28:40.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And New York Times columnist
Nicholas Kristof.

28:40.452 --> 28:43.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And welcome all three of you to
the program.

28:43.655 --> 28:49.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let me just each one of you to
say in brief,
how did we get to this point
five years in,

28:49.328 --> 28:53.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
half a million people dead in
Syria, millions
more displaced?

28:53.732 --> 28:55.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How did we get here, Derek
Chollet?

28:55.734 --> 28:59.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEREK CHOLLET, Former U.S.
Assistant Secretary
of Defense: Well, it's a very
difficult confluence

28:59.838 --> 29:01.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of issues.

29:01.673 --> 29:06.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a proxy war that is being
fought by many
countries in the region, and, of
course, the

29:06.478 --> 29:10.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russians, with many different
interests at
play.

29:10.315 --> 29:18.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a brutal regime, in the
Assad regime,
that is willing to take any
measure, no matter

29:18.290 --> 29:24.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how immoral or war criminal
acts, to persecute
its goals.

29:24.596 --> 29:29.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's very much driven by
fears in the
United States, legitimate fears,
I believe,

29:29.701 --> 29:35.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about escalation of any U.S.
military involvement,
and what that may lead to in
terms of an enduring

29:35.540 --> 29:38.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. commitment, military
commitment, inside
of Syria.

29:39.011 --> 29:41.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Nick Kristof, how
did we get
here?

29:41.446 --> 29:44.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS KRISTOF, Columnist, The
New York
Times: Well, I think that
President Obama

29:44.483 --> 29:51.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resisted the suggestions by
Hillary Clinton,
by David Petraeus, and others to
become more

29:51.256 --> 29:58.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
engaged, partly because it
seemed plausible,
in 2012 or even 2013, that Assad
was going

29:58.497 --> 29:59.965 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to fall anyway.

29:59.998 --> 30:04.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, why get engaged
if what we
want is going to happen anyway?

30:04.136 --> 30:07.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was, indeed, plausible,
but it also
proved wrong.

30:07.873 --> 30:12.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think also, more broadly,
in a place
like Syria, you know, there are
no good options.

30:12.577 --> 30:16.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in a situation like that,
it's always
easiest in any given day, if you
don't have

30:16.848 --> 30:20.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a good option, to say, well,
let's see what
we're going to do tomorrow.

30:20.385 --> 30:26.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's how bit by bit you
end up losing
half-a-million lives with no end
in sight.

30:26.491 --> 30:28.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Randa Slim, how
do you see
this?

30:28.660 --> 30:30.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did we get here?

30:30.429 --> 30:35.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RANDA SLIM, Middle East
Institute: I think
we started, the administration,
putting the

30:35.967 --> 30:43.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right set of objectives in 2011,
when the
president said that Assad must
step aside,

30:43.075 --> 30:48.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because it was rightly diagnosed
that the
primary driver of the conflict,
and still

30:48.413 --> 30:50.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is the case today, is the Assad
regime.

30:50.916 --> 30:58.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
However, I think the
administration proved
unwilling and -- to put together
the strategy

30:58.790 --> 31:03.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and to deploy the necessary
tools to make
that happen.

31:03.328 --> 31:09.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, as Nick said, there was
a strong
assumption that Assad will fall
or that Assad

31:09.134 --> 31:11.136 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can be convinced to transition
out.

31:11.169 --> 31:14.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think time and again, this has
proven to
be a wrong assumption.

31:14.940 --> 31:21.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, also, I think the other
factor is that
we were facing an opponent with
a coalition

31:21.513 --> 31:28.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
supporting it that has been
willing to endorse
and to engage in any kind of
tactic, in any

31:28.954 --> 31:35.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
kind of awful kinds of
intervention to stay
in power.

31:35.293 --> 31:42.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we have this coalition
now made up
of Russia, made up of Iran, made
up of Hezbollah,

31:42.200 --> 31:47.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
supporting Assad that is very --
has a clear
-- I would say, that has a clear
objective,

31:47.773 --> 31:54.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that has a clear strategy, and
that is willing
to deploy any tool at its
disposal, no matter

31:54.813 --> 31:57.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what -- how onerous it is, to
achieve that
objective.

31:57.382 --> 32:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me turn
back to Derek
Chollet.

32:00.485 --> 32:05.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Given all this, given where we
are, what is
the path forward?

32:05.090 --> 32:08.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And can the U.S. do something on
the own?

32:08.627 --> 32:14.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEREK CHOLLET: Well, it's very
difficult to
see a clear path forward, given
the extent

32:14.800 --> 32:20.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to which the Russians are now
involved in
this situation and the brutality
that Assad

32:20.038 --> 32:21.807 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has shown.

32:21.840 --> 32:24.409 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That said, I think it's
important for your
viewers to remember the United
States military

32:24.442 --> 32:28.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has been bombing Syria every day
for the last
two years.

32:28.547 --> 32:33.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, the targets the U.S.
military has been
hitting and the special
operators on the ground

32:33.251 --> 32:36.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been in support of the
Kurds and Arab
tribes in Syria.

32:36.988 --> 32:38.790 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The targets are counter-ISIL.

32:38.824 --> 32:44.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are some things to do
that we could
do in terms of expanding the
aperture of the

32:44.529 --> 32:50.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
airstrikes, perhaps putting some
of the regime
targets at risk that would be
risky, but I

32:50.402 --> 32:56.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
believe would limit the risk of
escalation
that the president has rightly
been concerned

32:56.208 --> 32:57.809 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
about.

32:57.843 --> 33:01.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's no question the U.S.
military has
the capability to take out a
regime.

33:01.446 --> 33:05.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have shown three times over
the last 15
years that the U.S. military can
take down

33:05.717 --> 33:06.685 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
regimes.

33:06.718 --> 33:07.686 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We did it in Afghanistan.

33:07.719 --> 33:08.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We did it in Iraq.

33:08.720 --> 33:10.455 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We did it in Libya.

33:10.488 --> 33:14.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The challenge is -- Judy, as you
suggested
in your opening piece, is, what
comes next,

33:14.593 --> 33:16.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and what can the U.S. do about
what comes
next?

33:16.761 --> 33:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that has been a
limiting factor
on the president's decision to
get more involved

33:21.833 --> 33:24.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
militarily in trying to bring
about a transition
inside Syria.

33:24.870 --> 33:27.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Nick Kristof, you
have written
about this extensively.

33:27.939 --> 33:31.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What realistically is the path
forward for
the U.S.?

33:31.309 --> 33:32.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We are late in the Obama
administration.

33:32.978 --> 33:36.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is going to be another
president in
the next few months.

33:36.915 --> 33:38.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What is a realistic path
forward?

33:38.917 --> 33:44.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Well, I mean,
I think what
we need to aim for is a
cease-fire and a kind

33:44.356 --> 33:50.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of de facto partition of Syria
among the sides,
with at least the fighting
stopping, and then

33:50.228 --> 33:54.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wait, and maybe some time down
the road, one
can put the pieces back together
again.

33:54.900 --> 33:59.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But to get that cease-fire, to
stop the killing,
then you need leverage.

33:59.704 --> 34:05.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Syrian government has
responded only -- not
to moral appeals, but only when
it feels threatened.

34:05.644 --> 34:10.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, in 2013, when it feared
that it was
going to be -- it was going to
suffer airstrikes

34:10.282 --> 34:14.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then, indeed, it agreed, you
know, we will
have hand over chemical weapons.

34:15.020 --> 34:19.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many, many of the members of
Parliament in
Syria fled the country because
there was a

34:19.324 --> 34:21.526 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
credible military threat.

34:21.559 --> 34:28.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that John Kerry
feels legitimately
that his efforts to negotiate a
cease-fire

34:28.733 --> 34:33.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were enormously undercut because
the White
House wouldn't give him that
kind of leverage.

34:33.571 --> 34:35.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, you know, look this is
hard.

34:35.707 --> 34:37.542 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It may not work.

34:37.575 --> 34:44.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have in fact imposed a de
facto no-fly
zone over parts of Northern
Syria to protect

34:44.849 --> 34:47.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.S. military advisers on
ground.

34:47.185 --> 34:52.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We could crater runways, for
example, that
Syrian military aircraft take
off of.

34:52.157 --> 34:55.293 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And these aren't perfect
solutions, but I
think they're better than
letting hundreds

34:55.327 --> 34:57.729 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of thousands of people die in
the coming years.

34:57.762 --> 35:00.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Randa Slim, is
any of this
realistic?

35:00.932 --> 35:04.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We heard the vice presidential
nominees last
night bring up solutions.

35:04.836 --> 35:08.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We just heard what Derek and
Nick have said.

35:09.007 --> 35:16.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does any of this, does it show
any relation
of what could, politically,
realistically

35:16.214 --> 35:17.649 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
take place?

35:17.682 --> 35:22.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
RANDA SLIM: To what
realistically takes place
in the United States?

35:22.687 --> 35:28.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think that, with this
administration,
given the time frame that's left
in its tenure,

35:28.493 --> 35:33.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, five weeks, less than
five weeks
away from the election, I don't
think that

35:33.264 --> 35:41.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this administration would engage
in any kind
of military option that bears
risks, and especially

35:41.339 --> 35:42.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
high risks.

35:42.741 --> 35:46.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And any option right now in
Syria is going
to be a risky option.

35:47.012 --> 35:52.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what we need to do and
what is realistic
is to alleviate the human
suffering.

35:52.650 --> 35:59.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is -- for example, we have
now 250,000
to 270,000 people that are under
siege by

35:59.991 --> 36:05.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Syrian regime and its
supporting coalition
in Eastern Aleppo, and that are
being basically

36:05.797 --> 36:07.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
starved to death.

36:07.665 --> 36:14.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so airdrops of humanitarian
aid, airdrops
over this region of medicine, of
food, massive

36:14.472 --> 36:22.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
airdrops of medicine and food in
the short-term,
could help at least alleviate
the human suffering

36:22.380 --> 36:24.115 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of these people.

36:24.149 --> 36:30.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we also need to, in the
short-term,
to enable the armed groups, the
opposition

36:30.288 --> 36:36.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's still in Eastern Aleppo
to stay there,
and we need to enable the armed
groups that

36:36.394 --> 36:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are fighting against ISIL and
that are fighting
against the regime to continue
to fight against

36:41.099 --> 36:42.934 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ISIL, against the regime.

36:42.967 --> 36:47.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there is this element here
that we always
are forgetting, that there are
regional parties

36:47.605 --> 36:53.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that have high stakes in this
conflict, either
the United States or Russia
today.

36:53.078 --> 36:58.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these are countries that are
going to
continue to wage their proxy
wars in Syria

36:58.483 --> 37:07.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and to, in a way, help change
the dynamics
on the ground in ways that best
serve the

37:07.125 --> 37:08.593 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
interests of the Syrian parties.

37:08.626 --> 37:10.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

37:10.428 --> 37:13.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, given that, Derek Chollet,
is the next
president going to have any more
success than

37:13.798 --> 37:15.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this one did?

37:15.533 --> 37:19.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we recognize the next
president could
have a different approach to
Syria.

37:20.004 --> 37:26.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEREK CHOLLET: Well, I think, as
Nick Kristof
said, this is a very difficult
problem.

37:26.611 --> 37:31.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there have been never been
easy, risk-free
solutions in Syria, whether
we're talking

37:31.616 --> 37:35.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in 2011, 2012, or today.

37:35.286 --> 37:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are a set of options that
the next president
will -- I'm certain will
consider, in terms

37:39.991 --> 37:44.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the attackers that targets
that we're hitting
with our airstrikes, in terms of
the kinds

37:44.229 --> 37:48.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of support we're giving the
Syrian option,
the kinds of weapons we are
providing them,

37:48.533 --> 37:52.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of the targets we are
directing the
Syrian opposition the hit, in
terms of the

37:52.170 --> 37:56.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
number of special operators on
the ground
to work with the Syrian
opposition to try

37:56.774 --> 37:59.978 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to make them more cohesive and
capable.

38:00.011 --> 38:04.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But none of those measures are
going to take
away the fundamental difficulty
of the situation

38:04.182 --> 38:09.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the dilemma that we're
facing, nor is
it going to take away the
significant risk

38:09.053 --> 38:12.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's entailed with any sort of
U.S. military
engagement in Syria.

38:12.457 --> 38:16.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's a risk we all
need to be
honest about and aware of as --
because I

38:17.028 --> 38:23.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think -- as we potentially
escalate further
into this conflict with no end
in sight perhaps.

38:23.067 --> 38:27.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, very
quickly, just to
give both Nick and Randa time
for a final

38:27.705 --> 38:33.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comment, at least will there be
a time for
an opportunity for a fresh start
with a new

38:33.711 --> 38:34.679 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president?

38:34.712 --> 38:36.447 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Quickly to Nick and then to
Randa.

38:36.481 --> 38:41.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Well, you
know, I think
there is going to be an
opportunity, but I

38:41.619 --> 38:45.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think Russia and Syria are both
frantically
trying to change the attacks on
the ground,

38:45.623 --> 38:48.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so that there is less room for
the next president
to maneuver.

38:48.893 --> 38:53.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the end of the day, I
mean, I guess
-- I think that President Obama
had a plausible

38:53.865 --> 38:58.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
strategy a few years ago, but
one that, in
retrospect, just has failed.

38:58.469 --> 39:03.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after a half-a-million
deaths, after the
rise of ISIS, after a global
refugee crisis,

39:03.541 --> 39:08.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then I think the one thing that
should be
pretty clear now is that it's
time to reevaluate

39:08.413 --> 39:10.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and look for a new approach.

39:10.248 --> 39:13.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Randa Slim,
what do we
look for?

39:13.985 --> 39:22.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RANDA SLIM: I think -- as Nick
said, I think
the next president will be
evaluating what

39:22.293 --> 39:24.195 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we need to do in Syria.

39:24.229 --> 39:31.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But also, as Nick said, I think
the next president
will be facing less options to
deal with.

39:31.202 --> 39:33.838 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meaning what?

39:33.871 --> 39:36.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Meaning that -- because the
Russians are now...

