52:06.623 --> 52:07.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is that?

52:07.891 --> 52:11.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Autophagy is
recycling at the
cellular level.

52:11.562 --> 52:13.063 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It happens inside our bodies.

52:13.097 --> 52:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For many years, scientists have
known about
lysosomes.

52:16.467 --> 52:21.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lysosomes are parts of our cells
that take
things that you don't
necessarily want there,

52:21.872 --> 52:26.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
potentially toxins, and breaks
them down into
their constituent parts to be
reused by the

52:26.777 --> 52:28.579 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
body.

52:28.612 --> 52:31.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What scientists never really
understood was,
how does the bad stuff get to
the lysosome?

52:31.715 --> 52:33.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's where autophagy comes
in.

52:33.784 --> 52:40.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Autophagosomes are essentially
the dump trucks,
the trash trucks of our body
delivering stuff

52:40.124 --> 52:42.226 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to our cells to be recycled.

52:42.259 --> 52:47.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this is potentially very
exciting, because
this might be at the very heart
of the very

52:47.264 --> 52:52.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
